@end example

@noindent
expands to:

@example
(let ((:a (make-keyword :a))
      (:b (make-keyword :b))
      (:c (make-keyword :c))
      (:d (make-keyword :d)))
  ---)
@end example
@end deffn


@deffn Syntax let-keywords @var{options} @var{allow-unknown} ((@var{name} @var{key} @var{default}) ...) @var{form0} @var{form} ...
@deffnx Syntax let-keywords* @var{options} @var{allow-unknown} ((@var{name} @var{key} @var{default}) ...) @var{form0} @var{form} ...
These are @func{let} and @func{let*} like macros that allow parsing a
list of keyword/value couples in @var{options}.  All the @var{key}
arguments must be keywords already defined.

@enumerate
@item
First all the @var{default} expressions are evaluated and their results
bound to the @var{name} identifiers, like with @func{let} or
@func{let*}.

@item
Then @var{options} is parsed and the values associated to the @var{key}
keywords are assigned to the @var{name} variables.

@item
Finally the @var{form} arguments are evaluated like in a @func{begin}
form.  The @var{form} arguments are the region of the @var{name}
bindings.
@end enumerate

