@section Binding accessors and mutators


All the following macros accept as argument the record name of a record
type.  For the macros to behave correctly, the record type definitions
must be available at expand time; this means the definitions have to be
put into a separate library:

@example
(library (record-types)
  (export <alpha> <beta>)
  (import (rnrs))

  (define-record-type <alpha>
    (fields (mutable a)
            (mutable b)))

  (define-record-type <beta>
    (parent <alpha>)
    (fields (mutable c)
            (mutable d))))
@end example

@noindent
and loaded appropriately:

@example
(import (rnrs)
  (records)
  (for (record-types) expand run))
@end example

@noindent
in the program or library making use of the macros.


@deffn Syntax define-record-accessors @var{record-name}
@deffnx Syntax define-record-accessors @var{record-name} @var{context-identifier}
Acquire the record type descriptor whose name is @var{record-name} and
bind its accessors to automatically generated names.  If the record
types hierarchy is:

@example
(define-record-type <alpha>
  (fields (mutable a)
          (mutable b)))

(define-record-type <beta>
  (parent <alpha>)
  (fields (mutable c)
          (mutable d)))
@end example

@noindent
the macro use:

@example
(define-record-accessors <beta>)
@end example

@noindent
defines:

@example
(define <beta>-a #<accessor of a in <alpha>>)
(define <beta>-b #<accessor of b in <alpha>>)
(define <beta>-c #<accessor of c in <beta>>)
(define <beta>-d #<accessor of d in <beta>>)
@end example

@noindent
