@section Macro transformers


The following bindings are exported by the @library{sexps syntax}
library.  Notice that to use it we may need to import the libraries with
the following specifications:

@example
(for (sexps)        expand run)
(for (sexps syntax) expand run)
(for (sentinel)     expand run)
@end example

Macros created by @func{define-sexp-macro} are meant to provide a
friendly syntax for record constructors and the like; example:

@example
(define-record-type (<alpha> %make-<alpha> <alpha>?)
  (fields (mutable a)
          (mutable b)))

(define-sexp-macro make-<alpha>
  ((?a 1) (?b 2))
  `(,(sexp-any (sexp-or `(a ,(sexp-var ?a))
                        `(b ,(sexp-var ?b)))))
  `(%make-<alpha> ,?a ,?b))

(let ((o (make-<alpha>)))
  (list (<alpha>-a o)
        (<alpha>-b o)))
@result{} (1 2)

(let ((o (make-<alpha> (a 10))))
  (list (<alpha>-a o)
        (<alpha>-b o)))
@result{} (10 2)

(let ((o (make-<alpha> (b 20))))
  (list (<alpha>-a o)
        (<alpha>-b o)))
@result{} (1 20)

(let ((o (make-<alpha> (a 10)
                       (b 20))))
  (list (<alpha>-a o)
        (<alpha>-b o)))
@result{} (10 20)

(let* ((the-a   10)
       (the-b   20)
       (o       (make-<alpha> (a the-a)
                              (b the-b))))
  (list (<alpha>-a o)
        (<alpha>-b o)))
@result{} (10 20)

(let* ((x 10)
       (y 20)
       (o (make-<alpha> (a (+ 2 x))
                        (b (- 2 y)))))
  (list (<alpha>-a o)
        (<alpha>-b o)))
@result{} (12 -18)
@end example

@noindent
if a sexp variable referenced in the output form is left unbound by the
input form, and its default value is the sentinel, an assertion
violation is raised at expand time.


@deffn Syntax define-sexp-macro @var{name} ((@var{var} @var{default}) ...) @var{pattern} @var{output}
Define a new macro and bind it to @var{name}.  The defined macro applies
a transformer to its arguments and builds a processed output form, which
is then evaluated at run time.

The @var{var} and @var{default} arguments are like the ones of
@func{let-sexp-variables}, and they define the set of variables needed
by the output form.

The @var{pattern} and @var{output} arguments are like the ones of
@func{make-sexp-transformer}, and they are used to build the transformer
procedure.
@end deffn

