@c page
@node matches intro
@section Introduction


@library{matches} is a simple generative pattern matcher; each pattern
is expanded into the required tests, calling a failure continuation if
the tests fail.  This makes the logic easy to follow and extend, but
produces sub-optimal code in cases where you have many similar clauses
due to repeating the same tests.

Nonetheless a smart compiler should be able to remove the redundant
tests.  For ``match let'' and ``destructuring bind'' type uses there is
no performance hit.

@c page
@node matches match
@section Basic pattern matching


@deffn Syntax match @var{sexp} @var{clause} ...
@deffnx {Auxiliary Syntax} =>
Match the S--expression @var{sexp} against the @var{clause} arguments;
each clause is one of:

@example
(@cmeta{pattern} . @cmeta{body})
(@cmeta{pattern} (=> next) . @cmeta{body})
@end example

@var{expr} is evaluated and matched against each @meta{pattern} in turn;
the first to succeed causes the corresponding @meta{body} forms to be
evaluated as in @func{begin}, and the remaining patterns are ignored.
However, if the @samp{next} identifier is labeled, it may be used as a
continuation to continue matching, allowing for additional runtime tests
on the pattern.

The syntax for the patterns is:

@table @samp
@item *
Matches anything.

@item literal
Matches with @func{equal?}.

@item (quote sexp)
A literal S--expression.

@item pattern-var
Matches anything and binds @samp{pattern-var} to it.

@item (pattern1 --- patternN)
Proper list of @math{n} elements.

@item (pattern1 --- patternN . patternN+1)
Improper list of @math{n} or more elements.

@item (pattern1 --- patternN patternN+1 ...)
List of @math{n} or more elements with terminating ellipsis; each
element of remainder must match @samp{patternN+1}.

@item #(pattern1 --- patternN)
Vector of @math{n} elements.

@item #(pattern1 --- patternN patternN+1 ...)
Vector of @math{n} or more elements with terminating ellipsis; each
element of remainder must match @samp{patternN+1}.

@item (and pattern ---)
If all of @samp{pattern} match.

@item (or pattern ---)
If any of @samp{pattern} match.

@item (not pattern ---)
If all @samp{pattern} don't match at all.

@item (? pred pattern ---)
If @samp{pred} is true and all @samp{pattern} match.

@item ($ proc pattern)
If @samp{pattern} matches the result of applying @samp{proc} to the
expression.

@item (get! @cmeta{symbol})
Match anything and bind to @meta{symbol} a thunk which, when evaluated,
returns the matched element itself.

@item (set! @cmeta{symbol})
Match anything and bind to @meta{symbol} a function which, when applied
to a value, replaces the expression with that value.  This involves the
use of @func{set-car!}, @func{set-cdr!} and other mutators.
@end table
@end deffn


@deffn Syntax match-let ((@meta{pattern} @meta{expression}) ...) . @meta{body}
@deffnx Syntax match-let @meta{variable} ((@meta{pattern} @meta{expression}) ...) . @meta{body}
@deffnx Syntax match-let* ((@meta{pattern} @meta{expression}) ...) . @meta{body}
@deffnx Syntax match-letrec ((@meta{pattern} @meta{expression}) ...) . @meta{body}
Match each @cmeta{expression} against each @meta{pattern} and, if all
the matches are successful, evaluate @cmeta{body} in the resulting
environment.  If a pattern does not match, a mismatch error is raised;
these syntaxes are meant to provide destructuring, not to test if an
S--expression matches a pattern.

@example
(match-let ((x 1))
  x)
@result{} 1

(match-let (((x . y) '(1 . 2))
            (z       3))
  (list x y z))
@result{} (1 2 3)
@end example

These syntaxes are matching extensions of the corresponding @rnrs{6}
@func{let} syntaxes.  Notice that:

@example
(match-let ((* 1))
  *)
@result{} 1
@end example

@noindent
normal binding of variables takes precedence over pattern matching.
@end deffn


@deffn Syntax match-lambda @meta{clause} ...
@deffnx Syntax match-lambda* @meta{clause} ...
Define a @func{lambda} which matches its arguments against a set of
patterns.

@example
(match-lambda @cmeta{clause} ...) @equiv{}
  (lambda (expr) (match expr @meta{clause} ...))

(match-lambda* @cmeta{clause} ...) @equiv{}
  (lambda expr (match expr @meta{clause} ...))
@end example
@end deffn


@deffn Syntax match-lambda @var{name} @meta{clause} ...
@deffnx Syntax match-lambda* @var{name} @meta{clause} ...
Define a @func{lambda} which matches its arguments against a set of
patterns, binding it to @var{name}.

@example
(match-define @cmeta{name} @cmeta{clause} ...) @equiv{}
  (define @cmeta{name} (match-lambda @cmeta{clause} ...))

(match-define* @cmeta{name} @cmeta{clause} ...) @equiv{}
  (define @cmeta{name} (match-lambda* @cmeta{clause} ...))
@end example

Examples:

@example
(match-define one
  ((x y) (+ x y)))

(one '(1 2))
@result{} 3

(match-define* two
  ((x y) (+ x y)))

(two 1 2)
@result{} 3
@end example
@end deffn

