@c page
@node schelog
@chapter Programming in Schelog


The @library{schelog} library is an embedding of Prolog--style logic
programming in Scheme. ``Embedding'' means we don't lose Scheme: We can
use Prolog--style and conventional Scheme code fragments alongside each
other.  Schelog contains the full repertoire of Prolog features,
including meta--logical and second--order (``set'') predicates, leaving
out only those features that could more easily and more efficiently be
done with Scheme subexpressions.

The library is a port to @rnrs{6} Scheme of Schelog by Dorai Sitaram.
The original code is available at:

@center @url{http://www.ccs.neu.edu/home/dorai/schelog/schelog.html}

@c @menu
@c * schelog simple::              Simple goals and queries.
@c * schelog predicates::          Predicates.
@c * schelog scheme::              Using Scheme expressions.
@c @end menu

@c @c page
@c @node schelog simple
@c @section Simple goals and queries


@c Schelog objects are the same as Scheme objects.  However, there are two
@c subsets of these objects that are of special interest to Schelog: goals
@c and predicates.  We will first look at some simple goals.

@c A @dfn{goal} is an object whose truth or falsity we can check.  A goal
@c that turns out to be true is said to succeed.  A goal that turns out to
@c be false is said to fail.

@c Two simple goals that are provided in Schelog are:

@c @example
@c %true
@c %fail
@c @end example

@c The goal @samp{%true} succeeds.  The goal @samp{%fail} always fails.

@c A Schelog user can query a goal by wrapping it in a @samp{%which} form:

@c @example
@c (%which () %true)
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c evaluates to @samp{()}, indicating success, whereas:

@c @example
@c (%which () %fail)
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c evaluates to @false{}, indicating failure.

@c @quotation
@c The second subexpression of the @samp{%which} form is the empty list
@c @samp{()}.  Later, we will see @samp{%whiches} with other lists as the
@c second subform.
@c @end quotation

@c Henceforth, we will use the notation:

@c @example
@c E @result{} F
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c to say that @samp{E} evaluates to @samp{F}.  Thus:

@c @example
@c (%which () %true) @result{} ()
@c @end example

@c @c page
@c @node schelog predicates
@c @section Predicates


@c More interesting goals are created by applying a special kind of Schelog
@c object called a @dfn{predicate} (or relation) to other Schelog objects.
@c Schelog comes with some primitive predicates, such as the arithmetic
@c operators @func{%=:=} and @func{%<}, standing for arithmetic ``equal''
@c and ``less than'' respectively.  For example, the following are some
@c goals involving these predicates:

@c @example
@c (%which () (%=:= 1 1)) @result{} ()
@c (%which () (%< 1 2))   @result{} ()
@c (%which () (%=:= 1 2)) @result{} #f
@c (%which () (%< 1 1))   @result{} #f
@c @end example

@c Other arithmetic predicates are @func{%>} greater than, @func{%<=} less
@c than or equal to, @func{%>=} greater than or equal to, and @func{%=/=}
@c not equal.

@c Schelog predicates are not to be confused with conventional Scheme
@c predicates (such as @func{<} and @func{=}).  Schelog predicates, when
@c applied to arguments, produce goals that may either succeed or fail.
@c Scheme predicates, when applied to arguments, yield a boolean value.
@c Henceforth, we will use the term ``predicate'' to mean Schelog
@c predicates.  Conventional predicates will be explicitly called ``Scheme
@c predicates''.

@c @menu
@c * schelog predicates facts::    Predicates introducing facts.
@c * schelog predicates rules::    Predicates with rules.
@c * schelog predicates goals::    Solving goals.
@c * schelog predicates extra::    Asserting extra clauses.
@c * schelog predicates local::    Local variables.
@c @end menu

@c @c page
@c @node schelog predicates facts
@c @subsection Predicates introducing facts


@c Users can create their own predicates using the Schelog form
@c @func{%rel}.  For example, let's define the predicate @func{%knows}:

@c @example
@c (define %knows
@c   (%rel ()
@c     (('Odysseus 'TeX))
@c     (('Odysseus 'Scheme))
@c     (('Odysseus 'Prolog))
@c     (('Odysseus 'Penelope))
@c     (('Penelope 'TeX))
@c     (('Penelope 'Prolog))
@c     (('Penelope 'Odysseus))
@c     (('Telemachus 'TeX))
@c     (('Telemachus 'calculus))))
@c @end example

@c The expression has the expected meaning.  Each clause in the @func{%rel}
@c establishes a fact: Odysseus knows TeX, Telemachus knows calculus, &c.
@c In general, if we apply the predicate to the arguments in any one of its
@c clauses, we will get a successful goal.  Thus, since @func{%knows} has a
@c clause that reads @samp{(('Odysseus 'TeX))}, the goal @code{(%knows
@c 'Odysseus 'TeX)} will be true.

@c We can now get answers for the following types of queries:

@c @example
@c (%which ()
@c   (%knows 'Odysseus 'TeX))
@c @result{} ()

@c (%which ()
@c   (%knows 'Telemachus 'Scheme))
@c @result{} #f
@c @end example

@c @c page
@c @node schelog predicates rules
@c @subsection Predicates with rules


@c Predicates can be more complicated than the above bald recitation of
@c facts.  The predicate clauses can be rules, eg,

@c @example
@c (define %computer-literate
@c   (%rel (person)
@c     ((person)
@c       (%knows person 'TeX)
@c       (%knows person 'Scheme))
@c     ((person)
@c       (%knows person 'TeX)
@c       (%knows person 'Prolog))))
@c @end example

@c This defines the predicate @func{%computer-literate} in terms of the
@c predicate @func{%knows}.  In effect, a person is defined as
@c computer--literate if they know @samp{TeX} and @samp{Scheme}, or
@c @samp{TeX} and @samp{Prolog}.

@c Note that this use of @func{%rel} employs a local logic variable called
@c @samp{person}.  In general, a @func{%rel} expression can have a list of
@c symbols as its second subform.  These name new logic variables that can
@c be used within the body of the @func{%rel}.

@c The following query can now be answered:

@c @example
@c (%which ()
@c   (%computer-literate 'Penelope))
@c @result{} ()
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c since Penelope knows TeX and Prolog, she is computer--literate.

@c @c page
@c @node schelog predicates goals
@c @subsection Solving goals


@c The above queries are yes/no questions.  Logic programming allows more:
@c We can formulate a goal with uninstantiated logic variables and then ask
@c the querying process to provide, if possible, values for these variables
@c that cause the goal to succeed.  For instance, the query:

@c @example
@c (%which (what)
@c   (%knows 'Odysseus what))
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c asks for an instantiation of the logic variable what that satisfies the
@c goal @code{(%knows 'Odysseus what)}.  In other words, we are asking,
@c ``What does Odysseus know?''

@c Note that this use of @func{%which} (like @func{%rel} in the definition
@c of @func{%computer-literate}) uses a local logic variable, what.  In
@c general, the second subform of @func{%which} can be a list of local
@c logic variables.  The @func{%which} query returns an answer that is a
@c list of bindings, one for each logic variable mentioned in its second
@c subform.  Thus:

@c @example
@c (%which (what)
@c   (%knows 'Odysseus what))
@c @result{} ((what TeX))
@c @end example

@c But that is not all that wily Odysseus knows.  Schelog provides a
@c zero--argument procedure (``thunk'') called @func{%more} that retries
@c the goal in the last @func{%which} query for a different solution.

@c @example
@c (%more) @result{} ((what Scheme))
@c @end example

@c We can keep pumping for more solutions:

@c @example
@c (%more) @result{} ((what Prolog))
@c (%more) @result{} ((what Penelope))
@c (%more) @result{} #f
@c @end example

@c The final @false{} shows that there are no more solutions.  This is
@c because there are no more clauses in the @func{%knows} predicate that
@c list Odysseus as knowing anything else.

@c @quotation
@c It is now clear why @samp{()} was the right choice for truth in the
@c previous yes/no @func{%which} queries that had no logic variables.
@c @func{%which} returns a list of bindings for true goals: The list is
@c empty when there are no variables.
@c @end quotation

@c @c page
@c @node schelog predicates extra
@c @subsection Asserting extra clauses


@c We can add more clauses to a predicate after it has already been defined
@c with a @func{%rel}.  Schelog provides the %assert form for this
@c purpose. Eg,

@c @example
@c (%assert %knows ()
@c   (('Odysseus 'archery)))
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c tacks on a new clause at the end of the existing clauses of the
@c @func{%knows} predicate.  Now, the query:

@c @example
@c (%which (what)
@c   (%knows 'Odysseus what))

@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c gives @samp{TeX}, @samp{Scheme}, @samp{Prolog}, and @samp{Penelope}, as
@c before, but a subsequent @code{(%more)} yields a new result:
@c @samp{archery}.

@c The Schelog form @func{%assert-a} is similar to @func{%assert} but adds
@c clauses before any of the current clauses.

@c Both @func{%assert} and @func{%assert-a} assume that the variable they
@c are adding to, already names a predicate (presumably defined using
@c @func{%rel}).  In order to allow defining a predicate entirely through
@c @func{%asserts}, Schelog provides an empty predicate value
@c @func{%empty-rel}.  @func{%empty-rel} takes any number of arguments and
@c always fails.  A typical use of the @func{%empty-rel} and @func{%assert}
@c combination:

@c @example
@c (define %parent %empty-rel)

@c (%assert %parent ()
@c   (('Laertes 'Odysseus)))

@c (%assert %parent ()
@c   (('Odysseus 'Telemachus))
@c   (('Penelope 'Telemachus)))
@c @end example

@c (Schelog does not provide a predicate for retracting assertions, since
@c we can keep track of older versions of predicates using conventional
@c Scheme features (let and set!).)

@c @c page
@c @node schelog predicates local
@c @subsection Local variables


@c The local logic variables of @func{%rel} and @func{%which} expressions
@c are in reality introduced by the Schelog syntactic form called
@c @func{%let}.  (@func{%rel} and @func{%which} are macros written using
@c @func{%let}.)

@c @func{%let} introduces new lexically scoped logic variables.  Supposing,
@c instead of

@c @example
@c (%which (what)
@c   (%knows 'Odysseus what))
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c we had asked:

@c @example
@c (%let (what)
@c   (%which ()
@c     (%knows 'Odysseus what)))
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c this query, too, succeeds five times, since Odysseus knows five things.
@c However, @func{%which} emits bindings only for the local variables that
@c it introduces.  Thus, this query emits @samp{()} five times before
@c @code{(%more)} finally returns @false{}.

@c @c page
@c @node schelog scheme
@c @section Using Scheme expressions


@c The arguments of Schelog predicates can be any Scheme objects.  In
@c particular, composite structures such as lists, vectors and strings can
@c be used, as also Scheme expressions using the full array of Scheme's
@c construction and decomposition operators.  For instance, consider the
@c following goal:

@c @example
@c (%member x '(1 2 3))
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c here, @func{%member} is a predicate, @samp{x} is a logic variable, and
@c @samp{(1 2 3)} is a structure.  Given a suitably intuitive definition
@c for @func{%member}, the above goal succeeds for @math{x = 1, 2, 3}.

@c Now to defining predicates like @func{%member}:

@c @example
@c (define %member
@c   (%rel (x y xs)
@c     ((x (cons x xs)))
@c     ((x (cons y xs))
@c       (%member x xs))))
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c Ie, @func{%member} is defined with three local variables: @var{x},
@c @var{y}, @var{xs}.  It has two clauses, identifying the two ways of
@c determining membership.

@c The first clause of @func{%member} states a fact: For any @var{x},
@c @var{x} is a member of a list whose head is also @var{x}.

@c The second clause of @func{%member} is a rule: @var{x} is a member of a
@c list if we can show that it is a member of the tail of that list.  In
@c other words, the original @func{%member} goal is translated into a
@c subgoal, which is also a @func{%member} goal.

@c Note that the variable @var{y} in the definition of @func{%member}
@c occurs only once in the second clause.  As such, it doesn't need you to
@c make the effort of naming it.  (Names help only in matching a second
@c occurrence to a first.)  Schelog lets you use the expression @samp{(_)}
@c to denote an anonymous variable.  (Ie, @samp{_} is a thunk that
@c generates a fresh anonymous variable at each call.)  The predicate
@c @func{%member} can be rewritten as:

@c @example
@c (define %member
@c   (%rel (x xs)
@c     ((x (cons x (_))))
@c     ((x (cons (_) xs))
@c       (%member x xs))))
@c @end example

@c @menu
@c * schelog scheme constructor::  Constructors.
@c * schelog scheme is::           The @func{%is} procedure.
@c * schelog scheme lexical::      Lexical scoping.
@c * schelog scheme type::         Type predicates.
@c @end menu

@c @c page
@c @node schelog scheme constructor
@c @subsection Constructors


@c We can use constructors (Scheme procedures for creating structures) to
@c simulate data types in Schelog.  For instance, let's define a
@c natural--number data type where @samp{0} denotes zero, and @samp{(succ
@c x)} denotes the natural number whose immediate predecessor is @var{x}.
@c The constructor @func{succ} can be defined in Scheme as:

@c @example
@c (define succ
@c   (lambda (x)
@c     (vector 'succ x)))
@c @end example

@c Addition and multiplication can be defined as:

@c @example
@c (define %add
@c   (%rel (x y z)
@c     ((0 y y))
@c     (((succ x) y (succ z))
@c       (%add x y z))))

@c (define %times
@c   (%rel (x y z z1)
@c     ((0 y 0))
@c     (((succ x) y z)
@c      (%times x y z1)
@c      (%add y z1 z))))
@c @end example

@c We can do a lot of arithmetic with this in place.  For instance, the
@c factorial predicate looks like:

@c @example
@c (define %factorial
@c   (%rel (x y y1)
@c     ((0 (succ 0)))
@c     (((succ x) y)
@c       (%factorial x y1)
@c       (%times (succ x) y1 y))))
@c @end example

@c @c page
@c @node schelog scheme is
@c @subsection The @func{%is} procedure


@c The above is a very inefficient way to do arithmetic, especially when
@c the underlying language Scheme offers excellent arithmetic facilities
@c (including a comprehensive number ``tower'' and exact rational
@c arithmetic). One problem with using Scheme calculations directly in
@c Schelog clauses is that the expressions used may contain logic variables
@c that need to be dereferenced. Schelog provides the predicate %is that
@c takes care of this. The goal:

@c @example
@c (%is X E)
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c unifies @var{X} with the value of @var{E} considered as a Scheme
@c expression.  @var{E} can have logic variables, but usually they should
@c at least be bound, as unbound variables may not be palatable values to
@c the Scheme operators used in @var{E}.

@c We can now directly use the numbers of Scheme to write a more efficient
@c @func{%factorial} predicate:

@c @example
@c (define %factorial
@c   (%rel (x y x1 y1)
@c     ((0 1))
@c     ((x y) (%is x1 (- x 1))
@c            (%factorial x1 y1)
@c            (%is y (* y1 x)))))
@c @end example

@c A price that this efficiency comes with is that we can use
@c @func{%factorial} only with its first argument already instantiated.  In
@c many cases, this is not an unreasonable constraint.  In fact, given this
@c limitation, there is nothing to prevent us from using Scheme's factorial
@c directly:

@c @example
@c (define %factorial
@c   (%rel (x y)
@c     ((x y)
@c      (%is y (scheme-factorial x 1)))))
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c or better yet, ``in--line'' any calls to @func{%factorial} with
@c @func{%is} expressions calling @func{scheme-factorial}, where the latter
@c is defined in the usual manner:

@c @example
@c (define (scheme-factorial n r)
@c   (if (= n 0)
@c       r
@c     (scheme-factorial (- n 1) (* r n))))
@c @end example

@c @c page
@c @node schelog scheme lexical
@c @subsection Lexical scoping


@c One can use Scheme's lexical scoping to enhance predicate definition.
@c Here is a list--reversal predicate defined using a hidden auxiliary
@c predicate:

@c @example
@c (define %reverse
@c   (letrec
@c     ((revaux
@c        (%rel (x y z w)
@c 	 (('() y y))
@c 	 (((cons x y) z w)
@c 	   (revaux y
@c 	     (cons x z) w)))))
@c     (%rel (x y)
@c       ((x y) (revaux x '() y)))))
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c @code{(revaux X Y Z)} uses @var{y} as an accumulator for reversing
@c @var{x} into @var{z}.  @var{y} starts out as @samp{()}.  Each head of
@c @var{x} is consed on to @var{Y}.  Finally, when @var{x} has wound down
@c to @samp{()}, @var{y} contains the reversed list and can be returned as
@c @var{z}.

@c @noindent
@c @func{revaux} is used purely as a helper predicate for @func{%reverse},
@c and so it can be concealed within a lexical contour.  We use
@c @func{letrec} instead of let because @func{revaux} is a recursive
@c procedure.

@c @c page
@c @node schelog scheme type
@c @subsection Type predicates


@c Schelog provides a couple of predicates that let the user probe the type
@c of objects.  The goal:

@c @example
@c (%constant X)
@c @end example

@c @noindent
@c succeeds if @var{x} is an atomic object, ie, not a list or vector.

@c The predicate @func{%compound}, the negation of @func{%constant}, checks
@c if its argument is indeed a list or a vector.

@c The above are merely the logic--programming equivalents of corresponding
@c Scheme predicates.  Users can use the predicate @func{%is} and Scheme
@c predicates to write more type checks in Schelog.  Thus, to test if
@c @var{x} is a string, the following goal could be used:

@c @example
